First visualise your character. What does he/she actually look like? Are they broad-shouldered? Build like a brick ****-house or a stick? Tall or short? This can help you already get a feel of what your character will be like 'mentally'. Also how they dress: It's pretty obvious that a guy carrying 15 swords is gonna be aggressive.<br>
Now ask yourself questions. 'What is this guy's daily routine' is a good one. 'What would they do if X happened?' is another good one. Imagine them in a variety of situations, and how they would react. That's pretty much it. If you can imagine yourself as the character, it helps a lot too. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uhomonculous.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Homonculous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/14/02 1:31:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1504.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mangatech.netfirms.com/laughing.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Character Psychology</span><hr size=1> I usually don't concentrate on the details too much b'coz time is valuable. my prime aim is only to get the natural movements right. <br>
